                                                                                                                <comments>
                            <comment id="14715566" author="aweisberg" created="Wed, 26 Aug 2015 21:36:26 +0000"  >&lt;p&gt;&lt;a href=&quot;https://issues.apache.org/jira/secure/ViewProfile.jspa?name=benedict&quot; class=&quot;user-hover&quot; rel=&quot;benedict&quot;&gt;benedict&lt;/a&gt; can you take a look? &lt;a href=&quot;https://github.com/apache/cassandra/compare/trunk...aweisberg:C-10203?expand=1&quot; class=&quot;external-link&quot; target=&quot;_blank&quot; rel=&quot;nofollow noopener&quot;&gt;Proposed fix available here&lt;/a&gt;. Still waiting on Cassci to pick up the branch.&lt;/p&gt;</comment>
                            <comment id="14715569" author="snazy" created="Wed, 26 Aug 2015 21:38:31 +0000"  >&lt;p&gt;Fix + tests: +1 (unless cassci complains)&lt;/p&gt;</comment>
                            <comment id="14715648" author="benedict" created="Wed, 26 Aug 2015 22:37:08 +0000"  >&lt;p&gt;+1 for the fix to commit and get release rolling again, but after that, I think we can:&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ol&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Make the whole of that runLength logic a little clearer&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Take a look at why our randomised testing didn&apos;t catch this. It looks like we&apos;re constraining the domain of randomisation unnecessarily with the phrase &quot;the very model of a modern major general ...&quot; - which, while pleasing to the eye, can probably be revisited to improve the utility of the test.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ol&gt;
</comment>
                            <comment id="14715675" author="aweisberg" created="Wed, 26 Aug 2015 22:59:18 +0000"  >&lt;p&gt;The randomization did do a large string some % of the time, but the max was set to 4000. I saw full coverage in emma and though I was done. Classic case of not looking at the boundaries.&lt;/p&gt;</comment>
                            <comment id="14715679" author="snazy" created="Wed, 26 Aug 2015 22:59:51 +0000"  >&lt;p&gt;Committed as 27bc7a5202761bcb8a12f7f7c7fba65ae1a19934&lt;/p&gt;</comment>
                            <comment id="14715720" author="benedict" created="Wed, 26 Aug 2015 23:18:04 +0000"  >&lt;p&gt;But we&apos;re still only covering lengthy strings, nothing interesting regarding dispersion of different values. &lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Really the existing fuzz tests should be modified to ensure they cover this and all other possible scenarios - however improbably. No harm having the new tests as well, but whenever we need a new test, it means our randomised testing is inadequate. It should cover empty strings, and huge strings with arbitrary contents.&lt;/p&gt;</comment>
                            <comment id="14715722" author="benedict" created="Wed, 26 Aug 2015 23:19:45 +0000"  >&lt;p&gt;We should also look to merge BufferedDataOutputPlusTest with DataOutputTest, and check all of our inputs and outputs are properly covered (in 3.0, for instance, we no longer need to wrap our SequentialWriter for testing)&lt;/p&gt;</comment>
